# Molding C8.5 Small – Pusher Error

## Issue
- Machine: Molding EQMLD00146
- Model: C8.5 Small
- Time: 22:00 (03/03/2023)
- Machine alarm: Error while pushing leadframes to the leadframe handler

## Symptom
- Machine showed a pusher-related alarm while pushing leadframes to the leadframe handler.

## Root Cause
- Root cause: Signal of sensor control pusher (3S7B) was not stable.
- Sensor 3S7B must always be ON before push-out panel.
- However, the sender and receiver positions of sensor 3S7B were not aligned.
- Because sender and receiver were not aligned, the signal became unstable.

## Failure Mechanism
- Sensor 3S7B is used as a control condition before panel / leadframe push-out.
- Due to sender / receiver misalignment, the sensor signal fluctuated and did not remain stable in the required ON state.
- Because the pusher control condition depended on this signal, unstable detection triggered the pusher error during leadframe transfer to the leadframe handler.

## Actions
- Re-aligned the sender and receiver positions of sensor 3S7B.
- Adjusted the sensitivity of sensor 3S7B.
- Tightened the fixing screws of the sensor position.
- Added marking on the machine for sensor position reference.
- Added sensor 3S7B check item into monthly maintenance.

## Current Status
- Machine recovered to normal condition from 10:00 AM (03/04/2023).
- Current status: recovered, continue monitoring for repeat signal instability.

## Impact
- Quality: no specific panel defect quantity stated in the slide
- Production: machine interruption until sensor realignment and adjustment were completed
- Safety: not stated in the report
- Repeat risk: possible if sensor position shifts again or monthly maintenance check is not sustained

## Open Risk / Follow-up
- Need to confirm long-term stability of sensor 3S7B signal
- Need to verify the monthly maintenance item is executed consistently
- Need to monitor whether sender/receiver position moves again during operation / vibration

